  "text": "# Firefox TLS Handshake Chain: Necko to NSS\n\n## Overview\n\nThis document traces the complete call chain for how Firefox initiates a TLS connection from the networking layer (Necko) through to the cryptographic layer (NSS/Network Security Services).\n\n## Hop 1: HTTP Protocol Layer\n\n**File:** `netwerk/protocol/http/nsHttpConnection.cpp`\n**Class:** `nsHttpConnection`\n**Key Function:** `EnsureSSLSetupComplete()`\n\nThe HTTP connection object manages the lifecycle of an HTTP connection. When handling HTTPS requests, it creates a `TlsHandshaker` instance that orchestrates SSL setup. The handshaker is stored as `RefPtr<TlsHandshaker> mTlsHandshaker` and receives calls to `SetupSSL()` to configure TLS parameters before initiating the connection.\n\n**File:** `netwerk/protocol/http/TlsHandshaker.cpp`\n**Class:** `TlsHandshaker`\n**Key Functions:** \n- `SetupSSL()` (line 72) - Initiates SSL configuration\n- `InitSSLParams()` - Configures SSL parameters and versions\n- `SetupNPNList()` - Builds ALPN/NPN protocol negotiation list\n- `EnsureNPNComplete()` - Drives handshake forward asynchronously\n\nThe `TlsHandshaker` class is responsible for all TLS-specific configuration before the handshake begins. It determines which TLS versions to support, which cipher suites are available, and which application-level protocols (ALPN) to advertise.\n\n## Hop 2: Socket Provider Registration\n\n**File:** `netwerk/socket/nsSocketProviderService.cpp`\n**Location:** Socket provider factory in `netwerk/socket/`\n\nThe socket provider service acts as a factory/registry that maps socket type strings (\"ssl\", \"starttls\", etc.) to their concrete implementations. For SSL connections, it provides the `nsSSLSocketProvider` implementation.\n\n## Hop 3: NSS I/O Layer Bridge\n\n**File:** `security/manager/ssl/nsSSLSocketProvider.cpp`\n**Class:** `nsSSLSocketProvider`\n**Key Function:** `NewSocket()` (line 28)\n\nThe SSL socket provider implements the `nsISocketProvider` interface. When `NewSocket()` is called, it delegates to the NSS I/O layer functions:\n\n**File:** `security/manager/ssl/nsNSSIOLayer.cpp`\n**Class/Functions:**\n- `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers` class (defines platform-specific SSL method tables)\n- `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers::Init()` - Initializes the custom I/O layer methods\n- `nsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()` (line 1247) - Creates a new NSPR PRFileDesc with custom I/O handlers\n- `nsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()` (line 1790) - Wraps an existing socket with SSL I/O methods\n- `nsSSLIOLayerConnect()` (line 163) - Connection handler registered in I/O method table\n\nThese functions create NSPR (Netscape Portable Runtime) file descriptors with custom I/O layer methods that intercept all socket operations (read, write, connect, close, etc.) to perform SSL/TLS operations. A `NSSSocketControl` instance is created to manage TLS-specific state.\n\n**File:** `security/manager/ssl/NSSSocketControl.cpp`\n**Class:** `NSSSocketControl`\n**Key Functions:**\n- `StartTLS()` - Initiates TLS on an existing connection\n- `DriveHandshake()` (line 242) - Drives the NSS handshake state machine forward\n- `SetHandshakeCallbackListener()` - Registers callbacks for handshake progress\n\n## Hop 4: NSS Cryptographic Core\n\n**File:** `security/nss/lib/ssl/sslsecur.c`\n**Key Functions:**\n- `SSL_ForceHandshake()` (line 383) - The main entry point that drives the TLS handshake\n- `ssl_SecureConnect()` (line 692) - Establishes secure connection\n- `SSL_ResetHandshake()` (line 176) - Resets handshake state\n\nWhen `SSL_ForceHandshake()` is called on a PRFileDesc, it executes NSS's internal TLS handshake state machine, repeatedly processing records and advancing through handshake states until the handshake completes or fails.\n\n**File:** `security/nss/lib/ssl/ssl3con.c`\n**Key Functions:**\n- `ssl_BeginClientHandshake()` (line 113) - Initializes client-side handshake\n- `ssl3_HandleClientHello()` (line 9254) - Server-side ClientHello message handling\n- `ssl3_HandleClientHelloPart2()` (line 9646) - Continuation of ClientHello processing\n\nThese functions implement the actual TLS protocol state machine, handling ClientHello/ServerHello messages, key exchange, certificate verification, and record protection setup.\n\n**File:** `security/nss/lib/ssl/tls13con.c`\n**Purpose:** TLS 1.3-specific protocol implementation when negotiated\n\n## Complete Call Chain\n\n```\nnsHttpConnection::EnsureSSLSetupComplete()\n  ↓\nTlsHandshaker::SetupSSL()\n  ├─ TlsHandshaker::InitSSLParams()\n  └─ TlsHandshaker::SetupNPNList()\n      ↓\nnsSSLSocketProvider::NewSocket()\n  ↓\nnsSSLIOLayerNewSocket()\n  ↓\nnsSSLIOLayerAddToSocket()\n  ├─ Create NSSSocketControl\n  └─ Register I/O layer methods\n      ↓\nnsSSLIOLayerConnect() [via custom I/O layer]\n  ↓\nNSSSocketControl::DriveHandshake()\n  ↓\nSSL_ForceHandshake(PRFileDesc*)\n  ├─ ssl_BeginClientHandshake() [client-side]\n  └─ ssl3_HandleClientHello() [server-side]\n      ↓\nTLS Record Processing & Encryption\n  (ssl3con.c / tls13con.c handle record layer)\n```\n\n## Key Integration Points\n\n1. **NSPR File Descriptor Wrapping:** Firefox wraps TCP sockets with custom NSPR I/O methods, creating a layered file descriptor stack where each layer intercepts operations.\n\n2. **Asynchronous Handshake:** The `TlsHandshaker` and `NSSSocketControl` classes work together to drive the handshake asynchronously using callbacks, allowing Firefox to remain responsive.\n\n3. **Platform Abstraction:** `nsSSLIOLayerHelpers` provides platform-specific implementations of socket operations, abstractions for getting/setting socket options, and platform-dependent TLS features.\n\n4. **Certificate Validation:** Before the handshake completes, `NSSSocketControl` coordinates with `SSLServerCertVerification` to validate the server's certificate chain.\n\n5. **ALPN/NPN Negotiation:** `TlsHandshaker::SetupNPNList()` configures which HTTP versions (h2 for HTTP/2, h2c, http/1.1) to negotiate, which NSS transmits during the ClientHello extension.\n\n## Repository\n\nAll files are located in the Mozilla Firefox repository (`mozilla/gecko-dev` on GitHub, or `mozilla-central` in Mercurial) at https://github.com/mozilla/gecko-dev\n\n## NSS Integration Note\n\nFirefox includes NSS as a submodule at `security/nss/`, but the modern Firefox build system may link against a system NSS or bundled version. The actual NSS code in `security/nss/lib/ssl/` implements the core TLS protocol and is the same NSS library used across Mozilla products."
}

